# ASML Investment Thesis

::summary
ASML remains one of the most strategically important companies in the semiconductor supply chain. This document captures the investment thesis as a set of structured claims, evidence, and risks that an agent can revisit each quarter.
::

## Thesis at a glance

::grid{columns=2}
:::card{title="Bull Case" icon="up"}
EUV demand stays structurally high as foundries push to 2 nm and below. ASML retains a *de facto* monopoly on leading-edge lithography for the rest of the decade.
:::

:::card{title="Bear Case" icon="down"}
Export restrictions, semiconductor cyclicality, and chipmaker capex pauses could compress orders for two to four quarters at a time.
:::
::

## Claims

::claim{id="asml-euv-moat" confidence=0.82}
ASML has a durable moat because it is the only supplier of EUV lithography systems at scale.
::

::evidence{for="asml-euv-moat" source="annual-report-2025"}
ASML continues to report strong demand for EUV systems from the leading-edge customers (TSMC, Samsung, Intel). High-NA EUV machines (EXE:5000) are sold out for 2026 and 2027 deliveries.
::

::claim{id="asml-china-exposure" confidence=0.6}
China revenue exposure is a tail risk, not a structural threat — most China demand is for trailing-edge DUV, which is already partially substitutable.
::

::counterevidence{for="asml-china-exposure" source="us-export-controls-2025"}
The 2025 update to US export controls may extend to deep-ultraviolet (DUV) immersion systems, which would meaningfully reduce ASML's serviceable China market.
::

## Risks

::risk{id="risk-china-restrictions" severity="high" owner="ferax564"}
Further US/EU export restrictions could reduce ASML's China revenue by a high single-digit to low double-digit percentage of total sales.
::

::risk{id="risk-cyclicality" severity="medium" owner="ferax564"}
Semiconductor capex is cyclical. A WFE downturn could compress ASML's near-term order book even as the long-term thesis holds.
::

